		Comment <a href="#c_1713676545">4</a> by Craig
		posted on 1/23/2008 at 10:25 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Hi - I've recently had to take on more of a director's role with my primary client. This role has frequently pushed me into meetings where the firm's principal and I are selling our services. CF-related projects make up 90%+ of our interactive business.</p><p>I do articulate all the regular stuff (rapid development, easier maintenance, etc.) but here are a couple of talking points I've used to great success:</p><p>1. Easy and efficient creation of printable web content in the form of PDFs<br>2. Excellent integration with RIAs (this point has gone over incredibly well)<br>3. Performance and stability (with CF8's insane improvements in speed/processing, I've been able to use this to our group's advantage)<br>4. Interoperability (we can use .NET objects previously built, Java extensibility, etc.)</p><p>I don't use it often but, every now and again, I do love to throw out the "you get what you pay for" line when hitting resistance to using CF over free servers ala PHP or Ruby.</p><p>Best,<br>Craig</p></div>
